<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,971,1502]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,420,971,998]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Diagnostic characters:</emphasis>
The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Billberg" authorityYear="1820" box="[479,588,972,998]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lithosiini">Lithosiini</taxonomicName>
moths are commonly called as lichen moths, because some are specialized in feeding on lichens. Adults are with rather narrow forewings and deep hindwings that may equal or exceed them in area. The monophyly of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Billberg" authorityYear="1820" box="[507,616,1044,1070]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lithosiini">Lithosiini</taxonomicName>
is supported by larval mandibles with an enlarged, basal molar area associated with the specialized diet of lower plants; there is a characteristic arrangement of the larval labral setae; the eggs are smooth with shallow depressions, rather than sculpted with networks of ridges (Kitching &amp; Rawling in 
<bibRefCitation author="Kristensen, N. P." box="[151,337,1152,1178]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="237 - 253" refId="ref69263" refString="Kristensen, N. P. (1999) Phylogeny of endopterygote insects, the most successful lineage of living organisms. European Journal of Entomology, 96, 237 - 253." type="journal article" year="1999">Kristensen 1999</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Holloway, J. D." box="[348,588,1152,1178]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refId="ref65309" refString="Holloway, J. D. (2001) The moths of Borneo. Part 7. Family Arctiidae, subfamily Lithosiinae. Malayan Nature Society, KualaLumpur, 486 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1603 / 0013 - 8746 (2008) 101 [40: LOANWN] 2.0. CO; 2" type="book" year="2001">
Holloway 
<emphasis box="[465,522,1152,1178]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,971,1502]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,519,1187,1214]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Diversity and distribution:</emphasis>
Indian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Billberg" authorityYear="1820" box="[606,715,1188,1214]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lithosiini">Lithosiini</taxonomicName>
comprise 419 species and five subspecies under 128 genera. Of the 128 genera reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[482,542,1224,1250]" name="India" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">India</collectingCountry>
, 67 genera are represented by single species, 58 genera by two to 20 species and three genera, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1854" box="[304,391,1260,1285]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[304,391,1260,1285]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Barsine</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1854" box="[406,479,1260,1286]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Cyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[406,479,1260,1286]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Cyana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1819" box="[541,679,1260,1286]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[541,679,1260,1286]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Miltochrista</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known by 21, 42, and 54 species respectively (
<figureCitation box="[1258,1321,1259,1286]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1078,1102]" captionTargetBox="[155,1426,192,1040]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[151,1436,181,1055]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 6. Species diversity of Indian Lithosiini genera" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5602588" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5602588/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig.6</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[1372,1432,1260,1286]" name="India" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Billberg" authorityYear="1820" box="[151,260,1296,1322]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lithosiini">Lithosiini</taxonomicName>
is most diverse in North-East 
<collectingCountry box="[611,669,1296,1322]" name="India" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">India</collectingCountry>
followed by Central Himalaya, East Himalaya, and West &amp; North- West Himalaya. Only one species is reported from Desert and no 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Billberg" authorityYear="1820" box="[876,985,1332,1358]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lithosiini">Lithosiini</taxonomicName>
are recorded from Trans-Himalaya (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1708,1732]" captionTargetBox="[348,1247,1170,1684]" captionTargetId="figure-31@13.[340,1247,1163,1685]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 7. Distribution of Lithosiini within the biogeographic zones/ subzones of India and among the records like ‘throughout India’, ‘North India’, and ‘India’" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5602590" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5602590/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,971,1502]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,348,1404,1430]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Food plants:</emphasis>
The larval diet is frequently algae and lichens, occasionally bryophytes, these being grazed on the surface of leaves, branches, tree trunks etc. that may lead to these higher plants being recorded erroneously as hosts. The cocoon can be dense or very large, net-like, incorporating larval setae (
<bibRefCitation author="Bendib, A. &amp; Minet, J." box="[995,1243,1476,1502]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="241 - 263" refId="ref57751" refString="Bendib, A. &amp; Minet, J. (1999 [2000]) Lithosiine main lineages and their possible interrelationships. 1. Definition of new or resurrected tribes (Lepidoptera: Arctiidae). Annales de la Societe entomologique de France, New Series, 35 (3 - 4), 241 - 263." type="journal article" year="1999">Bendib &amp; Minet 1999</bibRefCitation>
[2000]).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
